	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				IMHO this spell is nearly useless.  There is nothing it does where your mana cannot be spent better somewhere else.<BR>
<BR>
Where it is most mana-efficient, i.e. where there are three or more mobs, you are going to become the tank automatically because every mob but one is now beating on you. You have not killed any mobs. You are not going to be able to heal either. You can melee, but big whoop. Your purpose is to have the mobs hit the tanks, who have the AC and the big melee.<BR>
<BR>
So what if some mobs aggro you when you heal? This comes later in the fight and it is what the group is counting on you to do. They will now have a longer hate list. One or more of them will now be dead. Save your mana for heals and/or stuns.<BR>
<BR>
Furthermore, if you stick to the plan, your group will be a lot better organized. If you throw AofE and cannot heal, your battle plan goes out the window. The primary healer is now the caster, and who is healing? Everyone is fighting in total confusion when you use this spell and more mistakes are made.  And in this regard, AofE also causes tremendous lag.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, it is not generally useful to damage every mob a little, no matter how mana-efficient the cast. Four mobs with three-fourths of their HPs hit harder than three mobs with full HP and are harder to taunt onto the tanks.  <BR>
<BR>
I will not even allow casters to use AofE. You end up spending all of your mana healing a low-AC mage instead of the high-AC tanks. Make them use DD to kill the main mob, assisting the pulling tank.  <BR>
<BR>
Putting the entire group's assets into killing one mob at a time, focussing the strength, and having each player maximize his strongest powers, is the difference between fighting as a group and fighting as six individuals. It is MUCH more powerful to fight as a group.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
